  "text": "HTTP/1.1 to HTTP/2 header translation in Envoy is primarily handled through the HTTP/1 codec and header map implementation. The key migration involves three main aspects:\n\n1. **Header Case Normalization (Lowercase)**: In `source/common/http/http1/codec_impl.cc:565`, the `completeCurrentHeader()` method applies lowercase normalization to all header field names using `current_header_field_.inlineTransform([](char c) { return absl::ascii_tolower(c); })`. This ensures all headers are stored in lowercase, which is standard for HTTP/2.\n\n2. **Pseudo-Header Injection**: The `ServerConnectionImpl::onHeadersCompleteBase()` method (starting at line 1186 in codec_impl.cc) orchestrates the creation of HTTP/2 pseudo-headers. It calls `handlePath()` (lines 1100-1162) which sets:\n   - `:path` - Set via `headers.setPath(absolute_url.pathAndQueryParams())` at line 1159\n   - `:scheme` - Set via `headers.setScheme(absl::AsciiStrToLower(absolute_url.scheme()))` at line 1145 (with lowercase conversion)\n   - `:authority` - Set via `headers.setHost(absolute_url.hostAndPort())` at line 1141\n   - `:method` - Set via `headers->setMethod(parser_->methodName())` at line 1218\n\n3. **Upgrade Header Handling**: The `onHeadersCompleteImpl()` method (lines 836-949 in codec_impl.cc) manages HTTP upgrade requests. It detects upgrade requests using `Utility::isUpgrade()` from `source/common/http/utility.cc:627-633`, and handles special cases for h2c upgrades by removing unsupported upgrade headers (lines 849-871).\n\n4. **Pseudo-Header Detection**: The `isPseudoHeader()` method in `source/common/http/header_map_impl.cc:54` identifies pseudo-headers by checking if the first character is a colon (`:`). This is critical for distinguishing HTTP/2 pseudo-headers from regular headers.\n\n5. **HTTP/2 Integration**: In `source/common/http/http2/codec_impl.cc:643-645`, the `saveHeader()` method processes headers received on HTTP/2 streams, allowing integration with the header normalization pipeline.\n\nThe translation process ensures HTTP/1.1 requests are properly converted to HTTP/2 format with correctly normalized headers, proper pseudo-header values, and appropriate handling of connection and upgrade directives."
}

